{"SDAH1985:530": "In November 1873, Spafford put his wife and four daughters on the steamship Ville du Havre bound for Europe, held back at the last hour by business in Chicago. Nine days later a telegram from his wife reached him with two words at its head: \"Saved alone.\" The ship had been struck in the night and gone down in twelve minutes. All four girls — Annie, Maggie, Bessie, and Tanetta — were lost. Spafford sailed at once to bring Anna home. Somewhere mid-ocean the captain called him to the bridge and told him they were passing over the place where the Ville du Havre had sunk. Standing above that water, Spafford did not write of despair. He wrote to his sister that his daughters were \"safe, folded, the dear lambs.\" Out of that crossing, in the grief of the years just after, came the words: When peace like a river attendeth my way... it is well, it is well with my soul. His friend Philip Bliss set them to music and named the tune Ville du Havre, after the ship. ---", "SDAH1985:108": "The legend says Newton wrote this in the heat of a storm at sea, a slave-trader struck down and changed in an instant. The truth is slower and, in its way, more hopeful. Newton's turning began in a 1748 storm, but he went on working in the slave trade for years afterward; his conscience woke by degrees, not all at once. The hymn itself was written far from the sea. By 1772 Newton was a parish curate in the quiet town of Olney, and it was his custom each New Year to sit with his journal and take account of his life — the wreck he had been, the mercy that had found him. For the service on New Year's Day, 1773, he wrote a plain testimony in verse to go with his sermon: Amazing grace! how sweet the sound, that saved a wretch like me. He meant the word wretch exactly. It was not poetry. It was the ledger of a man who knew precisely what he had been spared from. ---", "SDAH1985:100": "Most great hymns are born of a single shattering hour. This one was not — and that is the whole point of it. Years later, asked what dramatic event lay behind the words, Chisholm answered plainly that there were no special circumstances at all. He was a Kentucky farm boy of little schooling and lifelong poor health, who taught school, sold insurance, and wrote quiet poems when his strength allowed. There was no shipwreck in his story, no deathbed, no miracle. There was only this: morning after ordinary morning, year upon modest year, he watched God provide what the day required. Reading Lamentations — they are new every morning: great is thy faithfulness — he recognized his own life in it. In 1923 he sent the poem to a musician friend, William Runyan, who set it to a tune he named Faithfulness. Its power is that it was written by no one special, about nothing remarkable — only a faithfulness so steady it could be overlooked, until someone finally set it to song. ---", "SDAH1985:50": "Lyte was dying when he wrote it. For more than twenty years he had served a fishing parish on the Devon coast, and tuberculosis was now taking the last of his strength. In the autumn of 1847, knowing he would soon leave for a warmer climate from which he did not expect to return, he climbed into his pulpit one final time and preached to his people, barely able to stand. That same evening he walked by the sea, and the line of a Gospel story was with him — the two travelers at Emmaus pressing their unrecognized Lord to stay as the light failed: Abide with us: for it is toward evening, and the day is far spent. Lyte went in and wrote his own version of that plea — not the evening of a single day, but the evening of a whole life: Abide with me; fast falls the eventide... when other helpers fail and comforts flee, help of the helpless, O abide with me. He died in Nice a few weeks later. The hymn was nearly his last act. ---", "SDAH1985:499": "Scriven never meant these words for the world. He had left Ireland for Canada carrying more sorrow than one man should — a first bride who drowned on the eve of their wedding, and later a second love lost to illness. He gave the rest of his life to the poor, often quietly giving away what little he had. Years on, word reached him that his mother, still in Ireland and far beyond his reach, was passing through a season of grief of her own. He could not go to her. So he did the only thing he could: he wrote her a poem, to comfort her across the ocean with the one steadfast companion he had found in all his own losses — What a friend we have in Jesus, all our sins and griefs to bear. It was a private letter from a grieving son to his hurting mother. Only by accident was it ever discovered to be a hymn at all. ---", "SDAH1985:462": "Blind from infancy, Crosby wrote thousands of hymns, most of them words set to tunes handed to her by others. This one was born in a single bright moment in a friend's parlor in 1873. Her friend Phoebe Knapp had composed a new melody and was eager for Crosby's opinion. She sat at the piano and played it through for the blind poet, then asked the question that became the hymn: \"What does this tune say?\" Crosby listened once, and the answer came up out of her at once, whole: \"Blessed assurance — Jesus is mine!\" The rest of the verses followed from that first phrase. She had never seen a sunrise or a friend's face, yet what she heard in a simple tune was certainty — a sightless woman singing this is my story, this is my song with a confidence the seeing rarely reach. ---", "SDAH1985:86": "The hymn the world sings began as a young Swede's walk home interrupted by a storm. In 1885, Carl Boberg was caught on the southeast coast of Sweden by a sudden, violent thunderstorm — wind off the bay, lightning splitting the sky. Then, as quickly as it came, it passed. The air went still, the sun returned over the glistening inlet, birds sang again, and from a distance came the sound of a church bell. That swift turn from terror to hush undid him. The vastness of the storm and the tenderness of the calm that followed felt like standing for a moment inside the power of God. He went home and wrote O store Gud — \"O Great God\" — his wonder set to a Swedish folk melody: Then sings my soul... how great Thou art. It traveled slowly, through Germany and Russia, before an English missionary gave it the words now known worldwide. A whole planet's worship traces back to one young man, one storm, and the silence after. ---", "SDAH1985:330": "Havergal wrote this in a single overflowing night of 1874, while a guest in a house full of people who did not all share her faith. It troubled her, and she made it her prayer that before she left, every person under that roof might be touched by God. The prayer was answered, person after person, until the whole household had been moved — and Havergal was too full to sleep. In the small hours, awake and overwhelmed with gratitude, the lines came to her one after another, each beginning with the same surrendered word: Take — Take my life... take my hands... take my voice... take my silver and my gold. It was not a poem composed at a desk but a consecration poured out in the dark, a woman handing God every separate piece of herself because He had just answered her so completely. Each couplet is a thing laid down. She spent the rest of her short life trying to mean every line. ---", "SDAH1985:76": "Matheson was blind, and on the evening of June 6, 1882, he was alone in his manse in Scotland while the rest of his family was away at his sister's wedding. Something in that day brought down on him a wave of anguish he would never fully explain — a private suffering he later said he could not describe to anyone. (He was firm, too, in denying the romantic legends that grew up around the hymn afterward.) In that hour of darkness the words came to him whole, so fast that he felt less like their author than their scribe. He wrote them in about five minutes and never altered a line — O Love that wilt not let me go, I rest my weary soul in thee. A blind man, sitting in his own kind of night while others celebrated, reached out and found that he was held by a Love that would not loosen its grip. The pain was real and the comfort was greater, and both are in every line. ---", "SDAH1985:313": "Elliott had once asked a visiting Swiss minister how she could come to God, feeling herself too unworthy. His answer stayed with her for life: come just as you are. Years later that gentle phrase became a hymn — born, fittingly, out of a day she felt utterly useless. An invalid for much of her life, Elliott was confined to her room while her family ran a busy charity bazaar downstairs to raise funds for a school. Listening to everyone work for a good cause she was too weak to join, she was overcome by her own helplessness — what use was she to anyone? Out of that low place she took up her pen and preached to herself the only gospel that could reach her there: that God receives the weak and the useless exactly as they are. Just as I am, without one plea... O Lamb of God, I come. She did not have to be strong, or well, or useful first. She only had to come. ---", "SDAH1985:501": "Fanny Crosby was blind from infancy, and prayer was the room she lived in. She could not read a printed page or see a friend's face, but she could go, any hour, into the presence of God — and she spoke of that hour the way other people speak of home. She composed in the dark of her own mind, holding a whole hymn complete in her memory, sometimes for days, before she ever dictated a word of it. Out of that life of constant, conversational prayer came this hymn — not about a single dramatic answer, but about the hour itself: the simple, repeated act of bending the heart toward God and finding rest there. 'Tis the blessed hour of prayer, when our hearts lowly bend. For a woman who could not see, the place of prayer was the one place she could always find her way to, and where she was never in the dark. It is a fitting song to open a prayer meeting, week after faithful week — a reminder that the gathering itself, the bowing together, is the gift.", "CIS1908:270": "Fanny Crosby was blind from infancy, and prayer was the room she lived in. She could not read a printed page or see a friend's face, but she could go, any hour, into the presence of God — and she spoke of that hour the way other people speak of home. She composed in the dark of her own mind, holding a whole hymn complete in her memory, sometimes for days, before she ever dictated a word of it. Out of that life of constant, conversational prayer came this hymn — not about a single dramatic answer, but about the hour itself: the simple, repeated act of bending the heart toward God and finding rest there. 'Tis the blessed hour of prayer, when our hearts lowly bend. For a woman who could not see, the place of prayer was the one place she could always find her way to, and where she was never in the dark. It is a fitting song to open a prayer meeting, week after faithful week — a reminder that the gathering itself, the bowing together, is the gift.", "SDAH1985:251": "Around 1933, Alfred Ackley was preaching a series of revival meetings when a young Jewish man, who had come several days running, stayed behind to put a hard question to him: why should he worship someone who had died centuries ago? Ackley answered without hesitating — that Jesus was not dead at all, but living, here and now, more alive than ever — and he set about trying to win the young man with that truth. The question would not leave him. On Easter morning he switched on the radio and heard a famous minister tell his listeners it made no difference whether Christ had truly risen, so long as His teaching lived on. Ackley was furious — it's a lie, he said. He preached the resurrection with everything he had that morning, and still the matter burned in him. That evening his wife told him to do the thing he did best: write a song. He sat down at the piano and answered both men at once — the skeptic and the preacher — with a single, ringing testimony that Christ is risen and present still. The hymn was his reply, and millions have made it their own. ---", "SDAH1985:280": "Joseph Hart spent his early years arguing against the very thing he would later sing. A clever, restless Londoner, he lived loosely and even wrote against the gospel, mocking those who preached free grace as if it gave people license to sin. For years he resisted, sure that he was too far gone or too unwilling to be reached. Then, in his mid-forties, the resistance broke. At a chapel in London, the grace he had argued against finally undid him, and he came — not cleaned up, not improved, but exactly as he was. Out of that surrender he began writing hymns for people like the man he had been, and in 1759 he published this one. Its whole genius is that it asks nothing of you first: Come, ye sinners, poor and needy... if you tarry till you're better, you will never come at all. Hart knew, because he had nearly tarried his whole life. It is the song to sing when shame says clean yourself up first — the answer is that you cannot, and you do not have to. You come needy, and that is the only requirement.", "CIS1908:178": "Joseph Hart spent his early years arguing against the very thing he would later sing. A clever, restless Londoner, he lived loosely and even wrote against the gospel, mocking those who preached free grace as if it gave people license to sin. For years he resisted, sure that he was too far gone or too unwilling to be reached. Then, in his mid-forties, the resistance broke. At a chapel in London, the grace he had argued against finally undid him, and he came — not cleaned up, not improved, but exactly as he was. Out of that surrender he began writing hymns for people like the man he had been, and in 1759 he published this one. Its whole genius is that it asks nothing of you first: Come, ye sinners, poor and needy... if you tarry till you're better, you will never come at all. Hart knew, because he had nearly tarried his whole life. It is the song to sing when shame says clean yourself up first — the answer is that you cannot, and you do not have to. You come needy, and that is the only requirement.", "CIS1908:28": "This hymn was born from a single image in Scripture. The prophet Zechariah had written of a day when a fountain would be opened... for sin and for uncleanness (Zechariah 13:1) — a spring that washes not dirt but guilt. Eden Latta, a prolific writer of gospel songs, took that one promise and turned it into a hymn a person could stand in. The picture is deliberately physical: a fountain of cleansing blood, and a sinner stepping into it to be made whiter than snow. Many who sing it have never known who wrote it or why — they only know the ache it answers, the longing to be truly clean. That is the quiet power of it. It does not argue; it invites you to be washed. For a congregation that has sung it for years without knowing its source, seeing the verse behind it — that ancient promise of an opened fountain — lets them sing it with new understanding, knowing the well they are drawing from is as old as the prophets.", "SDAH1985:388": "Here is one of the gentle surprises of hymn history. The blind poet Fanny Crosby — a lifelong Methodist who kept Sunday — first wrote these words with Sunday in mind, as a tender call to honor the Lord's day of worship. She never set out to write a Sabbath hymn. But the words she gave the church were larger than the day she meant them for. When Seventh-day Adventists, searching the Scriptures, came to honor the seventh-day Sabbath that God Himself had blessed at creation, they found in Crosby's lines exactly the joy they felt — Don't forget the Sabbath, the Lord our God hath blest, of all the week the brightest, of all the week the best. The hymn crossed over, embraced by a people who took its plea more literally than its author had imagined. There is grace in that: a sightless woman's song of delight in a holy day became, in other hands, a glad anthem for the commandment to remember. It is a reminder that what we offer God in good faith, He can carry further than we knew.", "CIS1908:250": "Here is one of the gentle surprises of hymn history. The blind poet Fanny Crosby — a lifelong Methodist who kept Sunday — first wrote these words with Sunday in mind, as a tender call to honor the Lord's day of worship. She never set out to write a Sabbath hymn. But the words she gave the church were larger than the day she meant them for. When Seventh-day Adventists, searching the Scriptures, came to honor the seventh-day Sabbath that God Himself had blessed at creation, they found in Crosby's lines exactly the joy they felt — Don't forget the Sabbath, the Lord our God hath blest, of all the week the brightest, of all the week the best. The hymn crossed over, embraced by a people who took its plea more literally than its author had imagined. There is grace in that: a sightless woman's song of delight in a holy day became, in other hands, a glad anthem for the commandment to remember. It is a reminder that what we offer God in good faith, He can carry further than we knew."}